513
00:30:04,230 --> 00:30:06,820
And the same "ro" as Ichiro
and Jiro! Genkiro!

514
00:30:06,820 --> 00:30:07,570
Nice to meet you!

515
00:30:07,570 --> 00:30:08,730
Uh...

516
00:30:08,730 --> 00:30:11,490
I'm Hashiba Kyoya. Likewise.

517
00:30:11,490 --> 00:30:15,110
So, Hashiba, did you play any sports?

518
00:30:15,110 --> 00:30:17,120
Not in particular, no.

519
00:30:17,120 --> 00:30:19,270
Just watched baseball on TV, really.

520
00:30:19,270 --> 00:30:23,650
Baseball, huh? Chibalotti
did great last year!

521
00:30:23,650 --> 00:30:27,660
And man, at last year's Koshien,
Koma-komai's Mii-kun was awesome!

522
00:30:27,660 --> 00:30:31,060
Oh, right... that would've
been ten years ago, huh?

523
00:30:31,060 --> 00:30:34,730
I guess the prince of towel's big showcase
is gonna be summer of this year...

524
00:30:34,730 --> 00:30:37,020
You a fan of any players, Hashiba?

525
00:30:37,020 --> 00:30:39,960
Uh...

526
00:30:39,960 --> 00:30:41,790
Maybe Oodani?

527
00:30:41,790 --> 00:30:45,530
Oodani? Doesn't ring any bells.

528
00:30:45,530 --> 00:30:47,580
You know, he's a two-way player.

529
00:30:47,580 --> 00:30:48,340
Who is?

530
00:30:48,340 --> 00:30:49,840
Oh, uh...

531
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:55,040
You, uh, ever think about that neat saying,
"He who chases two hares, won't catch one"?

532
00:30:55,430 --> 00:30:58,710
Crap, I need to choose
my words more carefully.

533
00:30:58,710 --> 00:31:02,730
Now then, we have the advising
assistant professor Kano here,

534
00:31:02,730 --> 00:31:06,340
who has a word for all of our new students.

535
00:31:06,340 --> 00:31:09,580
Hey there! Nice to meet you everybody!

536
00:31:09,580 --> 00:31:11,750
I'm Assistant Professor Kano.

537
00:31:11,750 --> 00:31:14,190
Welcome to art school!

538
00:31:14,190 --> 00:31:15,560
That's our teacher?

539
00:31:15,560 --> 00:31:17,540
She seems kinda young.

540
00:31:18,100 --> 00:31:23,440
Now, to start out with,
I'd like to take an informal survey.

541
00:31:23,440 --> 00:31:28,650
Okay, first of all, everyone wants
to direct movies, raise your hand!

542
00:31:29,770 --> 00:31:32,910
Okay, next, who wants to be a screenwriter?

543
00:31:33,960 --> 00:31:35,910
Anyone want to be an animator?

544
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:38,330
Game creators?

545
00:31:38,330 --> 00:31:42,520
There's plenty of others, right?
Filming, recording, effects, editing...

546
00:31:42,520 --> 00:31:44,480
All kinds of different careers!

547
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:47,310
I see, I see...

548
00:31:50,670 --> 00:31:54,350
Okay, you all need to listen up!

549
00:31:55,870 --> 00:32:00,770
First of all, we had 135 graduates
from the Visual Arts program last year.

550
00:32:00,770 --> 00:32:05,770
How many of them do you think
landed the job they were after,

551
00:32:05,770 --> 00:32:07,290
at the time of their admission?

552
00:32:07,290 --> 00:32:09,570
You there, blondie.

553
00:32:16,660 --> 00:32:19,120
U-Uh...

554
00:32:19,670 --> 00:32:22,150
Forty-two, maybe?

555
00:32:22,150 --> 00:32:24,500
Bzzt! Wrong.

556
00:32:25,170 --> 00:32:28,460
Even that many would be like a dream, huh?

557
00:32:29,670 --> 00:32:33,010
The correct answer is... eight of them.

558
00:32:34,360 --> 00:32:36,850
Is that less than you expected?

559
00:32:36,850 --> 00:32:40,040
And even that is better
than the previous year.

560
00:32:40,990 --> 00:32:44,860
Let's change subjects, for a sec,
and talk about money.

561
00:32:44,860 --> 00:32:50,040
People get hungry, they get tired,
and they have to use the bathroom.

562
00:32:50,040 --> 00:32:53,100
We need clothes to wear,
and homes to live in.

563
00:32:53,100 --> 00:32:54,370
I'm talking bare necessities.

564
00:32:54,370 --> 00:32:58,850
And because everybody needs them,
they cost money.

565
00:32:58,850 --> 00:33:02,540
But... how about movies,
anime, and video games?

566
00:33:02,850 --> 00:33:08,080
Entertainment only becomes important
once you've got your needs met.

567
00:33:08,080 --> 00:33:11,500
In other words, it's low priority.
Useless, you could even say.

568
00:33:11,500 --> 00:33:16,010
And you all, who have come to a university
to learn to make those things...

569
00:33:16,010 --> 00:33:18,350
Well, that goes all
the way past eccentricity...

570
00:33:18,350 --> 00:33:19,660
And into stupidity.

571
00:33:21,020 --> 00:33:25,270
Still, if you're good enough at being stupid?
You can make money off of it.

572
00:33:25,270 --> 00:33:26,870
That is what you need to seek out.

573
00:33:26,870 --> 00:33:30,930
If you're going to be stupid anyway,
do it in a way that no one else can touch.

574
00:33:31,530 --> 00:33:35,290
I'm looking forward to seeing that happen.

575
00:33:35,630 --> 00:33:36,750
That is all!

576
00:33:41,770 --> 00:33:45,310
"It's not gonna be easy," in other words.

577
00:33:46,440 --> 00:33:50,340
Now that I think about it, these
industries are not exactly expansive.

578
00:33:50,650 --> 00:33:55,120
Whether it's movies, anime, or games...

579
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:57,580
There's only a tiny fraction of people

580
00:33:57,580 --> 00:33:59,920
whose names get big enough
to become popular.

581
00:34:00,870 --> 00:34:04,130
Even if the people from this generation
were known as "Platinum,"

582
00:34:04,130 --> 00:34:07,930
it doesn't mean that every single one
of them shone bright.

583
00:34:07,930 --> 00:34:12,980
I should know, considering
the future I came from.

584
00:34:12,980 --> 00:34:16,240
But there's no sense in getting
depressed at the start.

585
00:34:17,670 --> 00:34:19,810
Gotta focus on getting things done.

586
00:34:22,370 --> 00:34:25,310
Excuse me, you dropped your student ID.

587
00:34:25,310 --> 00:34:27,290
Who, me?

588
00:34:31,850 --> 00:34:33,080
Wait, Chief?!

589
00:34:33,080 --> 00:34:37,420
Wait, what? I'm not in any
clubs or anything yet.

590
00:34:38,450 --> 00:34:39,430
Sorry.

591
00:34:41,430 --> 00:34:43,680
Uh... wait...

592
00:34:44,400 --> 00:34:47,100
Could you hand my ID over, please?

593
00:34:47,100 --> 00:34:48,690
Oh, right.

594
00:34:49,190 --> 00:34:50,190
Thanks.

595
00:34:56,480 --> 00:34:59,360
Huh, so she was in the same program.

596
00:35:07,430 --> 00:35:12,260
I might've been in the same room
as the Platinum Trio today!

597
00:35:13,920 --> 00:35:16,670
Two Weeks Later

598
00:35:16,840 --> 00:35:18,840
Scene 16, Cut 1...

599
00:35:18,840 --> 00:35:21,230
Ready... action!

600
00:35:22,460 --> 00:35:25,750
And so, our Visual Arts classes began.

601
00:35:25,750 --> 00:35:28,730
That said, it's not like we got
right into making movies.

602
00:35:29,150 --> 00:35:31,970
We observed the older students' shoots...

603
00:35:31,970 --> 00:35:35,570
And stuffed our heads full
of knowledge about the field.

604
00:35:39,220 --> 00:35:41,680
Damn it, what kind
of kaiju beats the superhero?!

605
00:35:41,680 --> 00:35:43,250
Sorry, heat of the moment...

606
00:35:43,680 --> 00:35:46,160
Freshmen, that was
an example of what not to do.

607
00:35:46,490 --> 00:35:49,830
Considering we were learning English verbs

608
00:35:49,830 --> 00:35:53,420
and secondary functions
just a few months ago...

609
00:35:53,420 --> 00:35:58,820
It's gonna take a while before things
like "the 180-degree rule" sink in.

610
00:35:59,430 --> 00:36:04,030
Although in my case,
I was 28 years old a month ago.

611
00:36:04,030 --> 00:36:05,830
You've got it all wrong!

612
00:36:06,420 --> 00:36:08,680
There's one exception, though.

613
00:36:08,680 --> 00:36:11,660
You're not positioned well.

614
00:36:11,660 --> 00:36:13,870
Give it another pause
before stepping into the scene.

615
00:36:13,870 --> 00:36:17,110
Camera, don't try and chase him down
with a pan. Pull out and hold.

616
00:36:17,620 --> 00:36:22,110
Kawasegawa was already
at the center of the action.

617
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:27,010
Although she's a little
imposingly serious at times.

618
00:36:27,010 --> 00:36:30,520
That's the chief for you.
She's on another level.

619
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:35,500
Screenplay Writing Theory

620
00:36:39,300 --> 00:36:41,190
Compared to that, here I am...

621
00:36:42,440 --> 00:36:46,100
wondering if I can really reach the level
of the Platinum Generation like this.

622
00:36:49,290 --> 00:36:51,430
Tsurayuki, wake up!

623
00:36:53,640 --> 00:36:59,320
Just a little bit more...
I'm wiped out from working all night.

624
00:37:00,990 --> 00:37:02,840
In spite of everything I said,

625
00:37:02,840 --> 00:37:06,700
the Share House Kitayama residents
seem to be taking things easy.

626
00:37:06,700 --> 00:37:09,450
If you wanted to be nice,
you could say they're relaxed.

627
00:37:09,450 --> 00:37:13,370
If you didn't, you could say they
don't seem motivated for class at all.

628
00:37:14,230 --> 00:37:16,120
Which is kind of a relief, to be honest.

629
00:37:17,210 --> 00:37:20,210
If everyone around me was like Kawasegawa...

630
00:37:20,730 --> 00:37:24,220
I think I might've been
afraid to attend class.

631
00:37:27,040 --> 00:37:30,320
Okay, when it comes to writing a script,

632
00:37:30,320 --> 00:37:32,720
there are ten elements you need
for things to come together.

633
00:37:32,720 --> 00:37:36,750
And yet you only see
eight here on the board.

634
00:37:32,720 --> 00:37:44,320
Screenplay Writing Theory
The Ten Points of Screenplay Writing

635
00:37:32,720 --> 00:37:44,320
Progress  Fate  Treasure  Resolution
Resonance  Climax  Conclusion  Themes

636
00:37:36,750 --> 00:37:40,580
Seems kind of weird when
there's supposed to be ten, right?

637
00:37:40,580 --> 00:37:45,930
Which is why I'm gonna ask you all
what the remaining two are.

638
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:47,030
Seriously?! I have no clue!

639
00:37:45,930 --> 00:37:47,030
Any ideas?

640
00:37:47,030 --> 00:37:47,990
Here.

641
00:37:47,990 --> 00:37:51,620
Well, someone's fired up. And you are?

642
00:37:52,230 --> 00:37:53,950
Kawasegawa Eiko.

643
00:37:53,950 --> 00:37:57,750
Is one of the missing
elements "complications"?

644
00:37:59,500 --> 00:38:03,290
"Complications" refers
to unpredictable turns in the story,

645
00:38:03,290 --> 00:38:06,220
which tend to lead into
the protagonist or hero failing.

646
00:38:06,730 --> 00:38:08,910
After all, no matter how
amazing an individual is,

647
00:38:08,910 --> 00:38:12,220
they're less interesting
without some kind of flaw.

648
00:38:12,590 --> 00:38:16,400
Having those faults come to the fore
during a story, and overcoming them,

649
00:38:16,400 --> 00:38:18,770
creates interesting drama.

650
00:38:21,370 --> 00:38:24,290
Correct you are. Perfect answer.

651
00:38:25,380 --> 00:38:26,820
She really is something.

652
00:38:26,820 --> 00:38:29,990
Can you tell me what the other one is, too?

653
00:38:29,990 --> 00:38:33,890
I'd hate to hog all the
attention. I think...

654
00:38:34,470 --> 00:38:37,570
I'd like to pass it off to the guy
who's snoring loudly behind me.

655
00:38:40,500 --> 00:38:46,130
You're an interesting one,
Kawasegawa-kun. And mean.

656
00:38:46,590 --> 00:38:47,800
Thank you, sir.

657
00:38:47,800 --> 00:38:51,050
And since you went ahead
and gave up the spotlight...

658
00:38:51,050 --> 00:38:53,680
Let's have sleepyhead here answer.

659
00:38:55,580 --> 00:38:57,730
Someone call for me?

660
00:38:57,730 --> 00:39:01,200
The professor did! He wants you
to name the missing element!

661
00:39:02,410 --> 00:39:03,690
Missing what?

662
00:39:03,690 --> 00:39:07,190
Ten Points of Screenplay Writing

663
00:39:07,190 --> 00:39:10,240
Complications

664
00:39:10,570 --> 00:39:13,240
Well? Don't you know?

665
00:39:13,240 --> 00:39:15,350
If you don't, then pay more attention toâ€”

666
00:39:15,350 --> 00:39:16,700
A foil.

667
00:39:18,650 --> 00:39:22,800
Someone who becomes the protagonist's
"enemy" in the story, in other words.

668
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:24,670
It can be an individual,
or an organization...

669
00:39:25,290 --> 00:39:27,910
Out of the other nine
principles you've got...

670
00:39:27,910 --> 00:39:31,680
A simple way of putting it would be
"whoever steals the treasure."

671
00:39:32,360 --> 00:39:35,940
Something to help maintain tension
until the climax of the story.

672
00:39:35,940 --> 00:39:38,640
I figure it's a pretty important element.

673
00:39:39,270 --> 00:39:40,550
Is that right?

674
00:39:42,840 --> 00:39:45,470
You're quite the complication yourself.

675
00:39:45,470 --> 00:39:47,820
But you're right. Well done.

676
00:39:48,250 --> 00:39:49,980
Thank you, sir.

677
00:39:55,460 --> 00:40:00,960
I take back what I said. Looks like
I won't be able to relax, after all.

678
00:40:00,960 --> 00:40:02,170
Pork
Katsu
Meal

679
00:40:00,960 --> 00:40:03,580
Mincemeat
Katsu
Meal

680
00:40:01,080 --> 00:40:04,960
Fried
Chicken
Meal

681
00:40:02,540 --> 00:40:04,960
Katsudon
with
Sauce

682
00:40:04,040 --> 00:40:04,960
Croquette
Meal

683
00:40:04,960 --> 00:40:06,960
It wasn't a big deal...

684
00:40:07,660 --> 00:40:10,920
I just recited something
I read in a book once.

685
00:40:10,920 --> 00:40:13,310
I don't see how that earns any praise.

686
00:40:13,310 --> 00:40:16,970
But that scary-looking teacher
flat-out praised you.

687
00:40:16,970 --> 00:40:18,670
Learn to take a compliment!

688
00:40:19,220 --> 00:40:22,490
He was just being nice to the freshman.

689
00:40:22,490 --> 00:40:25,070
Start taking that kind of thing seriously,
and you'll never get anywhere.

690
00:40:26,120 --> 00:40:30,560
Come on, Nanako. We've got
Visual Arts Theory for third period, right?

691
00:40:30,560 --> 00:40:32,110
Oh, right.

692
00:40:32,410 --> 00:40:34,110
See you two later.

693
00:40:35,970 --> 00:40:38,630
Tsurayuki-kun's really something.

694
00:40:38,630 --> 00:40:42,050
I don't get any of the jargon stuff,

695
00:40:42,050 --> 00:40:44,290
so I'm barely able to keep up.

696
00:40:44,290 --> 00:40:45,630
Same here.

697
00:40:46,780 --> 00:40:48,250
That said...

698
00:40:49,390 --> 00:40:53,050
I thought my extra ten years
would be an advantage.

699
00:40:53,050 --> 00:40:57,260
That it'd make a big difference compared
to all the other students.

700
00:40:58,080 --> 00:41:02,360
Even if it didn't amount to much,
I did actually work in entertainment.

701
00:41:02,360 --> 00:41:05,220
It was supposed to give me
some kind of advantage.

702
00:41:05,220 --> 00:41:07,160
But what I actually found out

703
00:41:07,160 --> 00:41:11,150
is that my fundamental
knowledge is severely lacking.

704
00:41:11,610 --> 00:41:16,110
A handful of sub-par experiences
isn't enough to equal knowledge or talent.

705
00:41:16,740 --> 00:41:19,100
It feels like I'm learning
that the hard way.

706
00:41:26,460 --> 00:41:30,430
What's wrong? You look real worried.

707
00:41:30,430 --> 00:41:31,630
O-Oh, no...

708
00:41:31,940 --> 00:41:35,380
It's nothing serious. Not really.

709
00:41:35,860 --> 00:41:37,570
If you say so...

710
00:41:38,960 --> 00:41:43,450
Come to think of it, why did Shinoaki...
apply to an arts school, anyway?

711
00:41:43,920 --> 00:41:47,190
She was paying close attention
in photography class, but...

712
00:41:47,560 --> 00:41:50,440
Maybe she wants to be a photographer?

713
00:41:54,150 --> 00:41:55,260
Hikawa?

714
00:41:55,260 --> 00:41:56,240
Yo!

715
00:41:56,240 --> 00:41:58,470
Why are you dressed like that?

716
00:41:58,470 --> 00:42:01,610
Come on, it's my club uniform!

717
00:42:01,610 --> 00:42:03,250
A... uniform?

718
00:42:03,250 --> 00:42:05,940
Hell yeah! There's only a handful
of them in the whole world...

719
00:42:05,940 --> 00:42:07,140
A ninja club!

720
00:42:07,140 --> 00:42:10,710
It's the Society for the Study
of Ninjutsu! I joined.

721
00:42:10,710 --> 00:42:12,780
I think I've heard of that, actually.

722
00:42:12,780 --> 00:42:15,610
In Japan, I think Oonaka Arts has the only one.

723
00:42:15,610 --> 00:42:18,220
Yeah! Nice and exclusive, know what I mean?

724
00:42:18,220 --> 00:42:22,010
Plus, one of the older
kunoichi girls is super hot.

725
00:42:22,520 --> 00:42:24,930
I bet that's why he joined.

726
00:42:24,930 --> 00:42:27,670
You sure are having fun, huh, Hikawa-kun?

727
00:42:27,670 --> 00:42:31,450
Hell yeah! You two should check
out some extracurricular stuff, too.

728
00:42:31,450 --> 00:42:32,940
It's seriously fun!

729
00:42:38,880 --> 00:42:42,450
Are these the club rooms?

730
00:42:42,450 --> 00:42:44,860
Seems like it.

731
00:42:45,910 --> 00:42:48,710
Nobody's home, though.

732
00:42:50,080 --> 00:42:51,500
Hey, hey!

733
00:42:52,690 --> 00:42:54,330
Up here, you two!

734
00:42:55,810 --> 00:42:57,340
You guys freshmen?

735
00:42:57,640 --> 00:42:58,900
Uh, yes.

736
00:42:58,900 --> 00:43:00,400
We are.

737
00:43:00,400 --> 00:43:03,760
I knew it! That settles things, then.

738
00:43:05,640 --> 00:43:11,020
The 2006 freshman mixer
is now officially underway!

739
00:43:11,020 --> 00:43:12,360
Cheers!

740
00:43:18,190 --> 00:43:23,560
We didn't even decide on a club
to join... Is this okay?

741
00:43:23,560 --> 00:43:25,530
I figure it is.

742
00:43:25,530 --> 00:43:28,930
They never asked us if we were in one!

743
00:43:30,080 --> 00:43:31,460
True enough.

744
00:43:53,270 --> 00:43:54,940
Say, Shinoaki...

745
00:43:55,480 --> 00:43:58,280
What do you want to do?

746
00:44:29,180 --> 00:44:31,250
Oh, you're awake?

747
00:44:32,430 --> 00:44:34,400
Kyoya-kun...

748
00:44:34,400 --> 00:44:36,200
Oh, sorry!

749
00:44:36,200 --> 00:44:38,030
It's fine. Don't worry about it.

750
00:44:38,390 --> 00:44:42,710
We've been busy non-stop
since the entrance ceremony, after all.

751
00:44:52,680 --> 00:44:57,960
You're pretty sharp, Kyoya-kun.
It's hard to believe we're the same age.

752
00:44:59,040 --> 00:45:01,210
You really think so?

753
00:45:01,210 --> 00:45:04,560
Yeah! You pay a lot
of attention to everybody.

754
00:45:04,560 --> 00:45:07,840
And you're calmer'n most
20-year-olds I know.

755
00:45:08,490 --> 00:45:13,200
But sometimes you look like you're
tired from thinking too hard.

756
00:45:13,770 --> 00:45:17,610
At lunch today, you looked real worried.

757
00:45:18,950 --> 00:45:21,740
It's nothing serious, though. I mean it.

758
00:45:22,400 --> 00:45:24,030
Ow, ow, ow...

759
00:45:24,030 --> 00:45:26,250
Quit trying to brush me off and talk!

760
00:45:26,680 --> 00:45:29,160
You might feel better that way.

761
00:45:33,430 --> 00:45:36,800
Well, today... seeing Tsurayuki in class...

762
00:45:36,800 --> 00:45:40,670
It made me realize how little I can do.

763
00:45:41,260 --> 00:45:43,680
No... it's not just him.

764
00:45:44,010 --> 00:45:47,430
Everybody at this school has something
that makes them special.

765
00:45:47,830 --> 00:45:51,810
But I've got nothing. So...

766
00:45:52,430 --> 00:45:56,440
I was thinking... about how little I can do.

767
00:45:56,740 --> 00:45:59,420
And it had me worrying a lot.

768
00:46:00,500 --> 00:46:05,850
That surprises me, because
I figured you could do anything.

769
00:46:05,850 --> 00:46:07,440
I can't, though.

770
00:46:09,210 --> 00:46:13,470
But you can cook
and keep yourself fed, right?

771
00:46:13,470 --> 00:46:14,270
Yeah...

772
00:46:14,270 --> 00:46:18,050
And do laundry, clean the house,
and keep things nice, right?

773
00:46:18,050 --> 00:46:19,330
I can do that.

774
00:46:19,330 --> 00:46:23,010
You can make plans
and actually stick to them, right?

775
00:46:23,010 --> 00:46:24,350
That too.

776
00:46:24,350 --> 00:46:28,340
I can't do any of that.

777
00:46:28,340 --> 00:46:32,600
I'm jealous of people
who can, if I'm being honest.

778
00:46:33,110 --> 00:46:37,160
Tsurayuki-kun probably feels the same way.

779
00:46:37,160 --> 00:46:41,900
There's bound to be stuff
he's jealous of you for.

780
00:46:42,970 --> 00:46:48,850
Folks who can't do anything
are all trying to find what we can do.

781
00:46:48,850 --> 00:46:54,210
So I bet even the people
you think are amazing

782
00:46:54,210 --> 00:46:56,120
are just as worried as you are.

783
00:47:06,390 --> 00:47:08,510
There, there.

784
00:47:11,540 --> 00:47:13,940
Shinoaki... listen...

785
00:47:16,350 --> 00:47:17,600
Thanks.

786
00:47:19,270 --> 00:47:22,230
I better do my best, too, huh?

787
00:47:23,760 --> 00:47:28,140
What can I do?

788
00:47:32,690 --> 00:47:34,080
We're home.

789
00:47:34,980 --> 00:47:37,060
I guess they're both at work.

790
00:47:37,060 --> 00:47:40,520
I'm gonna head to bed, then.

791
00:47:40,520 --> 00:47:41,350
Yeah.

792
00:47:43,100 --> 00:47:44,700
Our next report...

793
00:47:44,700 --> 00:47:50,150
A man was reported for causing
a scene in Dotonbori.

794
00:47:48,670 --> 00:47:52,100
I'm exhausted for today.
I'll work on my assignment tomorrow.

795
00:47:50,150 --> 00:47:52,090
When approached for a...

796
00:47:52,450 --> 00:47:54,000
I think I'll take a bath.

797
00:47:56,120 --> 00:47:59,100
Oh, I forgot to hand it to her.

798
00:48:02,820 --> 00:48:04,560
I wonder if she's asleep already.

799
00:48:07,360 --> 00:48:09,650
Shinoaki? Are you awake?

800
00:48:32,770 --> 00:48:37,130
Akishima Shino... is Shinoaki.

801
00:48:37,130 --> 00:48:42,850
Folks who can't do anything
are all trying to find what we can do.

802
00:48:43,220 --> 00:48:48,480
I see. That's what she wants to do, then.

803
00:48:50,800 --> 00:48:53,730
I need to find something, too.

804
00:48:55,590 --> 00:48:59,120
What do I want to do?

805
00:49:00,140 --> 00:49:02,720
And what is it that I can do?
